<P>
Opinion; Part 5; Page 5; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
758 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BAKER'S INAPPROPRIATE ROLE AS AN EVENHANDED BROKER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANE KIRKPATRICK, Jeane Kirkpatrick writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secretary of State Jim Baker's speech to the American Israel Political Action 
Committee last week is being widely interpreted as the first comprehensive, 
authoritative statement of the Bush Administration on the Arab-Israeli 
conflict. It is generally believed that its style and substance reflect the 
thoughts and feelings of the Bush-Baker team about problems of the region. 
</P>
<P>
Examination of the speech establishes that it is less harshly critical of 
Israel than was generally reported, especially on radio and television. 
Nonetheless, the speech was not good news for Israel and its friends, and is 
more likely to heighten tensions than lower them. 
</P>
<P>
The substantive proposals made by Baker were rendered less attractive than they 
might have been by some gratuitously negative language, which gave the speech 
its negative tone. 
</P>
<P>
"Stop the challenges to Israel's standing in international organizations," he 
told the Arabs; "repudiate the odious line that Zionism is racism." 
</P>
<P>
He told the Palestinians to renounce the policy of a phased takeover of Israel 
and to give up the uprising for diplomacy. 
</P>
<P>
To Israelis he said, "Forswear annexation. Stop settlement activity. Allow 
schools to reopen. Reach out to the Palestinians as neighbors who deserve 
political rights." 
</P>
<P>
There are important problems with Baker's speech. Most notable, perhaps, is the 
curious tone of evenhandedness in Baker's approach, the kind of assumption that 
fairness lies in a middle ground between Israeli and Palestinian goals, and his 
request that all parties -- Israelis, Palestinians and other Arabs -- make 
concessions. 
</P>
<P>
Baker referred in the introductory portions of his speech to the fact that 
Israel is a "vigorous democracy" with which the United States has a "strategic 
partnership." But his discussion of the conflict communicated no sense of 
greater concern for one side than for the other. It communicated no sense that 
Israel is a beleaguered democracy confronting a violent adversary bent on its 
destruction, no sense that Israel has fought three wars for survival. 
</P>
<P>
In a phrase seized on by the media, Baker called on Israel to "lay aside, once 
and for all, the unrealistic vision of a greater Israel." This is very strange 
language; it suggests that the secretary thinks that Israel is driven by an 
expansionist vision. But, of course, it was not expansionism that delivered the 
West Bank and Gaza to Israeli occupation. It was the need to defend against 
repeated attacks by neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
Baker's curious language becomes curiouser when it is remembered that in the 
since 1967, no Israeli government has acted to annex the territories, and that, 
to the contrary, in the one available opportunity to negotiate peace with an 
Arab neighbor, Israel returned the Sinai to Egypt in exchange for a very formal 
peace. In fact, no significant political party in Israel is driven by the 
vision of a "greater Israel." And to suggest otherwise is unfair and 
inaccurate. 
</P>
<P>
However, there is a state in the region driven by dreams of expansion. It is 
Assad's Syria, which occupies more than half of Lebanon. Jim Baker has yet to 
discuss this most-important obstacle to peace in the region. 
</P>
<P>
It is not clear why Baker should be more concerned with the peace and rights of 
Palestinians than of Lebanese. It is not clear why a U.S. secretary of state 
has a greater concern with peace on the West Bank than with peace in Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
Baker's goal for the West Bank and Gaza seems to me reasonable and compatible 
with the security of Israel, Jordan and West Bank Palestinians. His support of 
Israel's proposed plan for elections in the territories is consistent with our 
values and Israel's. His recognition that it will take time and concession by 
all is realistic. But his desire to be (or to seem to be) an evenhanded broker 
in a life-and-death struggle involving a faithful ally seems to me 
inappropriate. 
</P>
<P>
Responsibility for the Arab-Israeli conflict is not evenly distributed. This 
conflict was born of Arab refusal to accept the existence of a Jewish state, 
born of three Arab wars and of the refusal of Israel's neighbors even to 
discuss peace. It is a conflict that has led to the murder of Jews and 
Palestinians, and also of Anwar Sadat, Bashir Gemayel and other Arabs who have 
dared to advocate peace. It is a conflict that successive Israeli governments 
have sought to end -- even at great cost -- whenever a reasonable opportunity 
appeared. 
</P>
<P>
These are simple facts that need to be faced, even in this age when neutrality 
is often confused with reason and justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052889-0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 62873 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 28, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part 5; Page 5; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
967 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUDDENLY, TOM BRADLEY LOOKS MORTAL, AND L.A. BLACKS FEEL ORPHANED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JANET CLAYTON, Janet Clayton is an assistant editor of this page who 
previously covered local politics for The Times. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I've come home . . . I've come home." 
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, Mayor Tom Bradley spoke these words to launch his second 
ill-fated gubernatorial campaign at a rally of hundreds of black supporters who 
had jammed into a poorly ventilated room in South Los Angeles just to see and 
hear him. 
</P>
<P>
Tom Bradley has come home again. With the mayor's blessing, last week a 
gathering of black influentials rose to Bradley's defense as he faces the most 
serious crisis of his political career over questions about his financial 
dealings and allegations of conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
What was behind the stout, if belated, defense of the mayor has as much to do 
with deep concern for the future of all blacks in this city as it does with Tom 
Bradley's political future. The black leaders mounting the mayor's defense are 
afraid that without Bradley, the doors will shut again at a City Hall that was 
all but off-limits before he took office; in a broader sense, they fear that 
his absence will create an overall social and business environment more hostile 
to blacks in a city that already is strongly segregated. 
</P>
<P>
No matter what the disposition of the current investigations, the era of the 
71-year-old Bradley's quiet political dominance is in its twilight. And in 
spite of 16 years as mayor, Bradley, who has surrounded himself at the highest 
levels largely with people who represent his big business/Westside money base, 
has no political protege. 
</P>
<P>
Among the three blacks on the City Council, none appears able to forge the 
multiethnic coalition that Bradley attracted. 
</P>
<P>
Gilbert Lindsay, 88, represents a district with a boundary change possible in 
the future and a growing Latino population; there is a reasonable chance that 
the next representative will not be black. Robert Farrell, 51, has had to beat 
back two recall attempts. Nate Holden, 60, is a populist scrapper who ran 
against Bradley this spring. Holden proved himself adeptat tapping into 
widespread dissatisfaction about the quality of life in Los Angeles. But he did 
poorly against the mayor in the three predominantly black City Council 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
Ironically, many black political activists are pinning their highest hopes on a 
lawsuit initiated by the Mexican American Legal Defense and Education Fund. 
Either through creation of an expanded Board of Supervisors resulting from the 
lawsuit, or through natural succession to the seat currently held by Supervisor 
Kenneth Hahn, blacks are expecting a place on that powerful body. Rep. Julian 
Dixon, Assemblywoman Maxine Waters and Holden already have indicated interest. 
</P>
<P>
But in spite of its tremendous influence over health care, courts and 
environmental issues, the county board remains a nebulous entity to many 
voters. The mayor and council, like the President and Congress, are easily 
identifiable and thus most often looked to for leadership. And right now, the 
pool of younger blacks in position to ascend politically is limited. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley himself may have unwittingly fostered this dearth of local black 
political up-and-comers. When the mayor in 1987 put the power of his office 
behind the council candidacy of Homer Broome, a sincere but uncharismatic city 
commissioner with no electoral experience, the decision had a domino effect. 
Rita Walters, who wanted to run for the council, decided to stay on the school 
board. That set back Mark Ridley-Thomas, executive director of the local 
Southern Christian Leadership Conference and one of several young black 
professionals hungry for a chance to make a difference in politics. He found 
himself unexpectedly running against the well-supported incumbent Walters. The 
result: He lost, and another chance of political upward mobility for a new 
generation of black leaders was lost, too. And since incumbents rarely leave 
office, the "thirtysomething" hopefuls grow gray waiting for their turn at the 
political helm. 
</P>
<P>
So, many blacks cling to Bradley, with an interest less in protecting him 
personally and more as an act of self-preservation. 
</P>
<P>
"Even if you're not a fan of his," said one prominent black businessman, "if he 
goes out with a cloud over his head, it hurts us all." 
</P>
<P>
Many privately express worry that they will be forgotten in Los Angeles as 
Latino and Asian populations grow. It's an odd worry for a city that has the 
third-largest black population in the nation. But that infrequently quoted fact 
is little comfort to the blacks who have personalized Bradley's woes. 
</P>
<P>
Such a deep fear, which likely seems exaggerated to whites, is credible to many 
blacks. A January Los Angeles Times poll showed why with an ugly reality: 
Blacks are the group most disliked by others in Southern California. Although 
no poll was needed to confirm that to a black person, living daily with that 
knowledge has its deleterious effects -- like seeing racism as the motive when 
the press naturally goes after a big news story about Bradley's finances. 
</P>
<P>
The love-indifference-love relationship between Bradley and black voters was 
best described to me by a longtime resident who has known the mayor for several 
years. 
</P>
<P>
To the black community, this person said, Tom Bradley "is like the cousin in 
your family who was bright and managed against all odds to get to college and 
do better than anyone else in the family, and everyone's so proud. Then the 
cousin moves to the other side of town and visits less often because he's busy 
and successful. You understand. But as time goes on and baby brother needs 
shoes and mom gets sick, you sort of resent him for not doing more (to help). 
But when someone outside of the family attacks him, you end up leaping to his 
defense -- though you may think about it awhile first." 
</P>
<P>
And so to the degree that the black community ties its fate to that of the 
mayor, both face some difficult times and hard questions ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
