<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON AGING: SUPPLEMENTING THE BENEFITS OF MEDICARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By The UCLA-USC Longterm Care Gerontology Center 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
How many private health-insurance policies does it take to supplement Medicare 
benefits? Answer: one. And only one, because by law so-called Medigap policies 
must provide coverage for what Medicare does not: the $564 deductible for 
hospital costs, the $75 deductible for physicians' services and the 20% of 
Medicare-approved doctor charges. A second policy duplicates coverage. 
</P>
<P>
Says Robert Hunt of the National Insurance Consumer Organization: "Anyone who 
tries to sell a person more than one (Medigap policy) is trying to take the 
customer." So far, about 5.6 million older Americans have been taken, according 
to a 1987 study by the Health Insurance Assn. of America. That many people own 
two or more Medigap policies. 
</P>
<P>
Often they've been misled. It's illegal to knowingly sell a supplemental policy 
duplicating the purchaser's existing coverage, so unscrupulous sales persons 
may not ask if you already own a Medigap policy. They'll just try to sell you 
theirs. 
</P>
<P>
Here are some common sales pitches and facts for deciphering them: 
</P>
<P>
 -- A Social Security or Medicare worker comes calling to sell you a Medigap 
policy. Don't believe it. Representatives of these federal programs don't sell 
or service such insurance. 
</P>
<P>
 -- A salesman explains that Medicare does not cover extended stays in a 
nursing home, then pitches a Medigap policy. His statement is true as far as it 
goes: Medicare helps pay for care in a skilled-nursing facility for only 150 
days and does not cover stays of any length in intermediate- or custodial-care 
nursing homes. But the agent's misled you by implying that Medigap policies 
cover lengthy nursing-home stays. They don't. Consumers can purchase insurance 
policies that cover long-term care, but these are currently distinct from 
Medigap policies and do not supplement Medicare hospital and physician 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
 -- A Medigap insurance agent asks if you'd be interested in a policy that 
helps prevent you from ever becoming a burden to your spouse or children. With 
your worst fears running rampant, you have difficulty resisting the sales 
pitch. Again, the implication is that Medigap insurance offers coverage for 
long-term care. Once again, it doesn't. 
</P>
<P>
If you're worried about what will happen if you ever need extended care, 
discuss your concerns with family members and explore such options as 
long-term-care insurance or buying into a continuing-care retirement community. 
</P>
<P>
 -- An insurance rep asks if you'd like coverage for prescription drugs. You 
would, because your current Medigap policy doesn't provide this benefit. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to paying for items required by federal and state laws, some 
higher-priced Medigap polices provide extra insurance for prescription drugs, 
physician fees in excess of Medicare-approved charges or other benefits. 
Monthly premiums for these policies pay for the standard Medigap insurance plus 
the additional coverage. 
</P>
<P>
If you want broader coverage than your current Medigap policy provides, 
exchange it for one that meets your needs. Don't buy an extra Medigap policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
