<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIFE IN 'FAST LANE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Fast-Lane Environments" predicting that future commuters will ignore clean air 
plans and spend more time "car-cooning" on the freeways was dismaying at the 
very least. 
</P>
<P>
As a newcomer to Southern California, I've received an overwhelming impression 
of a public longing for a solution to jammed freeways and smog and willing to 
abide by rules and regulations if fairly applied. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, a dearth of leadership means there is no one in government or 
the press with the guts to demand that the people be 
</P>
<P>
served. 
</P>
<P>
We could start by insisting that the automotive designers -- so intent upon 
providing us with car phone, fax &amp; TV -- give us a small one-person 
commuter vehicle that would not only conserve fuel but would save room on the 
highways. And, oh yes -- It could be made comfortable as well. 
</P>
<P>
MARGARET SMITH 
</P>
<P>
Riverside 
</P>
