<HEADLINE>
<P>
MARATHONERS WHO RUN HOT, COLD; 
</P>
<P>
HYPOTHERMIA CHIEF ENEMY OF INEXPERIENCED RUNNERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I've started two marathon races, but both times I've had to drop out 
because I got overheated. But I've heard stories about other marathoners that 
had to drop out of a race because they got too cold. How can it ever be 
possible for someone who is running in a marathon to become too cold? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: I assume that neither of the marathons in which you participated was 
held on a cold, windy or wet day. If you try this some time, you will find that 
heat loss (hypothermia) can be a serious problem. 
</P>
<P>
Hypothermia is most likely to occur if the runner proceeds at a relatively slow 
pace. Among inexperienced marathoners (which, I believe, would include you), 
the critical time comes during the second half of the race when fatigue causes 
the runner to slow the pace. At such times, the body may very well be losing 
heat faster than it is producing it. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Is there any explanation for the fact that some children are simply more 
graceful than others? For example, some boys seem to be natural athletes, while 
others have two left feet. Why should there be such a difference in children? 
</P>
<P>
A: What you are describing may simply be two ends of a spectrum of motor 
skills. At one end are the natural athletes; at the other, less gifted 
children. 
</P>
<P>
It has been suggested that some clumsiness may be the result of minimal brain 
damage. Once this has been ruled out, it would seem that children simply differ 
in relation to their motor skills just as they differ in intelligence and other 
traits. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I'm just beginning to realize how many conditions are being treated with 
hypnosis. I've heard of its being used by dentists and by women at the time 
they give birth. Would it ever be possible for a child to be hypnotized? 
</P>
<P>
A: The peak age for susceptibility to hypnosis has been reported to range from 
7 to 10 years; it then declines with age. Children can also learn self-hypnosis 
more easily than is possible with adults. 
</P>
<P>
Q: You have mentioned at various times that a loss of weight and poor sleep are 
symptoms of depression. Is this always true? 
</P>
<P>
A: Weight loss and insomnia can be symptoms of depression. However, a person 
may experience weight loss and impaired sleep because of some medical condition 
or even as a side effect of medication. Similarly, sleep disturbance due to the 
need for frequent urination would not be considered a symptom of depression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052889-0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 62981 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 28, 1989, Sunday, Valley Edition 
</P>
