<HEADLINE>
<P>
76.4% OF DENTISTS NOW WEAR GLOVES DURING TREATMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of dentists using gloves when treating patients has jumped by more 
than 53% in recent years, according to a national survey by the American Dental 
Assn. 
</P>
<P>
The report, published in the May issue of the American Journal of the American 
Dental Assn., said 5,800 dentists were randomly surveyed between January and 
May of last year. 
</P>
<P>
Of those responding, 76.4% said they now wear gloves. In a similar 1986 survey, 
Only 22.7% said they wore gloves. 
</P>
<P>
ADA guidelines to prevent transmission of infectious diseases in the dental 
profession include the use of gloves, masks and eye wear with every patient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
